WEBVTT

1
00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:19.087
All her life she had wanted
to teach at Wellesley College.


2
00:01:19.257 --> 00:01:22.283
So when a position opened
in the Art History department...


3
00:01:22.460 --> 00:01:26.191
...she pursued it single-mindedly
until she was hired.


4
00:01:31.903 --> 00:01:34.133
It was whispered
that Katherine Watson...


5
00:01:34.572 --> 00:01:36.836
...a first-year teacher
from Oakland State...


6
00:01:37.008 --> 00:01:40.239
...made up in brains
what she lacked in pedigree.


7
00:01:50.689 --> 00:01:53.351
Which was why this bohemian
from California...


8
00:01:53.525 --> 00:01:57.859
...was on her way to the most
conservative college in the nation.


9
00:01:58.029 --> 00:02:00.623
- Excuse me, please.
- Oh, sorry.


10
00:02:02.334 --> 00:02:03.995
Excuse me.

11
00:02:08.506 --> 00:02:10.337
Excuse me. The bus?

12
00:02:10.508 --> 00:02:12.203
- Keep walking, ma'am.
- Thank you.


13
00:02:12.377 --> 00:02:16.143
But Katherine Watson didn't come
to Wellesley to fit in.


14
00:02:16.681 --> 00:02:20.742
She came to Wellesley because
she wanted to make a difference.


15
00:02:20.919 --> 00:02:24.548
- Violet.
- My favorite Italian professor.


16
00:02:24.723 --> 00:02:26.691
- Nice summer?
- Terrific, thanks.


17
00:02:26.858 --> 00:02:29.019
- Who's that over there?
- Where?


18
00:02:29.194 --> 00:02:33.858
Oh, Katherine Watson. New teacher.
Art History. I'm dying to meet her.


19
00:03:35.293 --> 00:03:38.160
Who knocks at the Door of Learning?

20
00:03:38.329 --> 00:03:42.891
- I am every woman.
- What do you seek?


21
00:03:43.067 --> 00:03:45.661
To awaken my spirit
through hard work...


22
00:03:45.837 --> 00:03:48.101
...and dedicate my life
to knowledge.


23
00:03:48.273 --> 00:03:49.706
Then you are welcome.

24
00:03:49.874 --> 00:03:54.971
All women who seek to follow you
can enter here.


25
00:03:55.146 --> 00:03:59.879
I now declare
the academic year begun.


26
00:04:19.103 --> 00:04:23.631
A shame you didn't come yesterday.
It's so quiet before the girls arrive.


27
00:04:26.344 --> 00:04:29.711
Just a few rules.
No holes in the walls.


28
00:04:29.881 --> 00:04:34.511
No pets, no loud noises, no radio
or hi-fi after 8 on weekdays...


29
00:04:34.686 --> 00:04:36.381
...10 on weekends...

30
00:04:36.554 --> 00:04:40.012
...no hot plates and no male visitors.

31
00:04:42.427 --> 00:04:43.985
Anything wrong?

32
00:04:44.896 --> 00:04:48.457
I don't think I can go a year
without a hot plate.


33
00:04:52.570 --> 00:04:55.562
Don't you just love chintz?

34
00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:57.605
And look.

35
00:05:01.646 --> 00:05:03.443
They match.

36
00:05:03.615 --> 00:05:07.551
Sweet, right? Your room's here.

37
00:05:07.719 --> 00:05:11.746
My room is just across the way...

38
00:05:12.323 --> 00:05:15.019
...and Amanda Armstrong's
down the other end.


39
00:05:15.660 --> 00:05:18.322
- You grew up here?
- My whole life.


40
00:05:18.496 --> 00:05:22.330
You'll meet my parents
when they come to visit.


41
00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:25.799
- They visit?
- Regularly.


42
00:05:28.306 --> 00:05:33.972
- What do you teach?
- Speech, elocution and poise.


43
00:05:34.412 --> 00:05:36.846
Dinners are communal,
so I'll handle that.


44
00:05:37.015 --> 00:05:40.610
But breakfast and lunch,
you're on your own. So...


45
00:05:40.785 --> 00:05:45.848
...we each get our own shelf.
I'll make your label this evening.


46
00:05:46.291 --> 00:05:52.230
I don't need to tell you, everything on
our individual shelves is sacrosanct.


47
00:05:54.065 --> 00:05:57.728
I just knew when we met...

48
00:05:58.636 --> 00:06:01.036
...we'd be instant friends.

49
00:06:19.190 --> 00:06:23.752
Be careful. They can smell fear.

50
00:06:44.082 --> 00:06:46.915
- Good morning.
- Good morning.


51
00:06:47.251 --> 00:06:48.912
Thank you.

52
00:06:49.654 --> 00:06:54.523
This is History of Art 100.

53
00:06:55.093 --> 00:06:59.120
We'll be following
Dr. Staunton's syllabus.


54
00:06:59.297 --> 00:07:02.266
- Any questions so far?
- Your name?


55
00:07:03.267 --> 00:07:05.633
- Why don't you go first?
- Connie Baker.


56
00:07:05.803 --> 00:07:10.467
- Katherine Watson. Nice to meet you.
- Dr. Watson, I presume.


57
00:07:11.576 --> 00:07:14.807
- Not yet. And you are?
- Giselle Levy.


58
00:07:14.979 --> 00:07:17.539
Giselle. If someone could get the...

59
00:07:18.816 --> 00:07:22.752
- Susan Delacorte.
- Thank you, Susan Delacorte.


60
00:07:26.257 --> 00:07:31.194
From the beginning, man has always
had the impulse to create art.


61
00:07:31.362 --> 00:07:34.798
- Can anyone tell me what this is?
- Wounded Bison, Altamira, Spain...


62
00:07:34.966 --> 00:07:38.231
...about 15,000 B.C.
Joan Brandwyn.


63
00:07:38.703 --> 00:07:40.603
Very good, Joan.

64
00:07:40.972 --> 00:07:44.965
Despite the age of these, they are
technically sophisticated because...


65
00:07:45.143 --> 00:07:49.637
The shading and the thickness of the
lines moving over the bison's hump.


66
00:07:49.814 --> 00:07:53.750
- Is that right?
- Yes, that's exactly right.


67
00:07:54.519 --> 00:07:56.510
Next slide.

68
00:07:57.055 --> 00:08:01.116
This is probably less familiar.
It was discovered by archeologists...


69
00:08:01.292 --> 00:08:05.251
In 1879, Lascaux, France.
Dates back to 10,000 B.C.


70
00:08:05.430 --> 00:08:09.730
Singled out because of flowing lines
depicting the movement of the animal.


71
00:08:11.869 --> 00:08:14.599
- Impressive. Name?
- Herd of Horses.


72
00:08:14.772 --> 00:08:17.969
- I meant yours.
- We call her Flicka.


73
00:08:18.609 --> 00:08:21.373
Elizabeth Warren.
They call me Betty.


74
00:08:21.546 --> 00:08:23.138
Very good.

75
00:08:23.314 --> 00:08:25.976
Betty is also correct.

76
00:08:26.150 --> 00:08:30.052
Just because something is ancient
doesn't mean that it is primitive.


77
00:08:30.221 --> 00:08:32.451
For example. Next slide, please.

78
00:08:32.623 --> 00:08:35.114
Mycerinus and His Queen. 2470 B.C.

79
00:08:35.293 --> 00:08:37.784
It's a funerary statue
of the pharaoh and queen...


80
00:08:37.962 --> 00:08:42.262
...originally intended to preserve
the pharaoh's ka. Soul.


81
00:08:45.837 --> 00:08:48.772
Have any of you taken
Art History before?


82
00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:51.170
No.

83
00:08:53.911 --> 00:08:56.505
Let's go on. Slide.

84
00:08:56.881 --> 00:08:59.782
Seated Scribe. Egypt. 2400 B.C.

85
00:09:00.718 --> 00:09:04.347
Peasant Couple Plowing.
Sixteenth century B.C. Egypt.


86
00:09:04.989 --> 00:09:08.083
Snake Goddess.
Minoan. 1600 B.C.


87
00:09:08.860 --> 00:09:10.794
Fresco. Minoan. 1600 B.C.

88
00:09:11.696 --> 00:09:13.857
Funeral Mask. Mycenaean. 1200.

89
00:09:26.244 --> 00:09:27.609
Could someone please get...?

90
00:09:34.418 --> 00:09:36.079
Thank you.

91
00:09:37.622 --> 00:09:41.023
By a show of hands only...

92
00:09:41.859 --> 00:09:46.023
...how many of you have read
the entire text?


93
00:09:48.499 --> 00:09:53.869
- And the suggested supplements.
- Long way from Oakland State?


94
00:09:57.308 --> 00:09:59.742
Well, you girls do prepare.

95
00:09:59.911 --> 00:10:03.677
If you've nothing else for us,
we could go to independent study.


96
00:10:04.582 --> 00:10:06.209
Ac...

97
00:10:42.954 --> 00:10:49.086
I was in California once. How do you
get work done with all that sunshine?


98
00:10:49.427 --> 00:10:53.056
- We tan in class.
- Really?


99
00:10:53.331 --> 00:10:54.628
No.

100
00:10:58.936 --> 00:11:01.530
You know, not everybody
wanted you.


101
00:11:01.706 --> 00:11:04.197
I'm not naming any names.

102
00:11:04.375 --> 00:11:08.971
These jobs usually go quickly.
Ex-students, friends of, you know...


103
00:11:09.146 --> 00:11:11.478
...the right people.

104
00:11:11.649 --> 00:11:15.585
The person they wanted took a job at
Brown, and no one else was available.


105
00:11:15.753 --> 00:11:17.846
So here you are.

106
00:11:18.689 --> 00:11:22.489
You can go in now. Good luck.

107
00:11:28.499 --> 00:11:31.297
Your first class left a lot
to be desired, Miss Watson.


108
00:11:31.469 --> 00:11:35.132
And I'm curious about the subject
of your dissertation.


109
00:11:35.306 --> 00:11:40.243
You suggest, "Picasso will do
for the 20th century...


110
00:11:40.411 --> 00:11:44.370
...what Michelangelo did
for the Renaissance," unquote.


111
00:11:45.116 --> 00:11:47.584
In terms of influencing movements.

112
00:11:47.752 --> 00:11:50.949
So these canvases that
they're turning out these days...


113
00:11:51.122 --> 00:11:54.182
...with paint dripped
and splotched on them...


114
00:11:54.358 --> 00:11:59.318
...they're as worthy of our attention
as Michelangelo's Sistine Chapel?


115
00:11:59.864 --> 00:12:01.661
I'm not comparing them.

116
00:12:01.832 --> 00:12:05.461
Have you ever seen
the Sistine Chapel, Miss Watson?


117
00:12:05.636 --> 00:12:07.627
Actually stood there?

118
00:12:09.273 --> 00:12:11.138
I've never been to Europe.

119
00:12:14.412 --> 00:12:19.213
I can assure all of you this is the place
I want to be more than anything.


120
00:12:19.383 --> 00:12:23.877
Better discipline next class,
Miss Watson.


121
00:12:29.226 --> 00:12:31.456
- Hello.
- It's me.


122
00:12:31.963 --> 00:12:34.659
- Hey!
- Collect from Katherine Watson.


123
00:12:34.832 --> 00:12:38.393
- Will you accept?
- Yeah, sure, of course I will.


124
00:12:39.036 --> 00:12:41.231
Hey, is everything okay?

125
00:12:42.506 --> 00:12:43.495
Yeah.

126
00:12:44.809 --> 00:12:46.401
Tough, huh?

127
00:12:49.513 --> 00:12:52.004
Well, how are the classes?

128
00:12:52.650 --> 00:12:54.584
Snobs, right?

129
00:12:55.886 --> 00:12:59.982
- I hate to say I told you so.
- You don't have to.


130
00:13:06.530 --> 00:13:08.657
I can't really talk right now.

131
00:13:09.867 --> 00:13:11.801
I'll write you tonight.

132
00:13:15.940 --> 00:13:17.430
So you got a fella?

133
00:13:18.909 --> 00:13:22.140
He's... He's there. I'm here.

134
00:13:22.313 --> 00:13:27.774
Long distance. Torture. I know.
Come. Come in and sit down.


135
00:13:31.455 --> 00:13:35.619
When Lenny left for the South Pacific,
it nearly broke my heart.


136
00:13:35.793 --> 00:13:38.523
We wrote every day until...

137
00:13:41.198 --> 00:13:43.291
He was a great man.

138
00:13:44.101 --> 00:13:47.036
- I'm sorry.
- It was a hundred years ago.


139
00:13:47.204 --> 00:13:49.001
I'm babbling.

140
00:13:51.242 --> 00:13:56.270
I love Lucy.
Even if she is a communist.


141
00:13:56.447 --> 00:13:59.314
The only thing red about Lucy
is her hair.


142
00:13:59.483 --> 00:14:01.951
And even that's fake. Desi said it.

143
00:14:02.119 --> 00:14:04.053
Winchell wrote it.

144
00:14:04.822 --> 00:14:07.757
Amanda Armstrong.
I see you survived.


145
00:14:07.925 --> 00:14:09.790
Katherine Watson. Just barely.

146
00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:13.088
Oh, good. You've met.
Katherine's taken the third bedroom.


147
00:14:13.264 --> 00:14:16.256
How about a little dinner
before What's My Line?


148
00:14:17.301 --> 00:14:19.826
How about a little drink?

149
00:14:22.206 --> 00:14:25.039
Her companion died in May.

150
00:14:25.576 --> 00:14:26.907
Companion?

151
00:14:27.745 --> 00:14:30.111
You know, companion.

152
00:14:31.248 --> 00:14:37.244
Josephine Burns.
Taught biology here for 30 years.


153
00:14:40.624 --> 00:14:43.752
You'll love it here, Katherine.
You'll see.


154
00:14:43.928 --> 00:14:48.865
I already do. I... Honestly,
it's beautiful. It's perfect, really.


155
00:14:49.033 --> 00:14:53.595
Well, don't fool yourself. They have
claws underneath their white gloves.


156
00:14:54.905 --> 00:14:56.372
Who?

157
00:14:57.174 --> 00:15:01.702
The alumnae, their offspring,
the faculty. You name it.


158
00:15:02.079 --> 00:15:03.876
Watch out for yourself.

159
00:15:04.048 --> 00:15:06.107
Too much independence
frightens them.


160
00:15:06.283 --> 00:15:10.049
- Will you please stop?
- Oh, a word of advice.


161
00:15:10.221 --> 00:15:13.622
Don't let those girls
know that they got to you.


162
00:15:16.127 --> 00:15:19.187
- They didn't.
- Good for you.


163
00:15:20.664 --> 00:15:22.928
You almost convinced me.

164
00:15:53.264 --> 00:15:56.199
- What is that?
- You tell me.


165
00:15:59.637 --> 00:16:03.471
Carcass by Soutine. 1925.

166
00:16:04.408 --> 00:16:07.900
- It's not on the syllabus.
- No, it's not.


167
00:16:09.914 --> 00:16:12.178
Is it any good?

168
00:16:17.421 --> 00:16:22.051
Come on, ladies.
There's no wrong answer.


169
00:16:22.226 --> 00:16:25.718
There's also no textbook
telling you what to think.


170
00:16:26.730 --> 00:16:28.789
It's not that easy, is it?

171
00:16:29.900 --> 00:16:32.232
All right. No. 
It's not good.

172
00:16:32.403 --> 00:16:35.201
In fact, I wouldn't even call it art.
It's grotesque.


173
00:16:35.406 --> 00:16:37.271
Is there a rule against
grotesque art?


174
00:16:37.474 --> 00:16:40.932
I think there's something
aggressive about it...


175
00:16:41.679 --> 00:16:44.842
...and erotic.
- To you, everything is erotic.


176
00:16:45.015 --> 00:16:47.415
- Everything is erotic.
- Girls.


177
00:16:47.585 --> 00:16:49.815
- Aren't there standards?
- Of course.


178
00:16:49.987 --> 00:16:53.354
Otherwise a tacky velvet painting
could be equated to a Rembrandt.


179
00:16:53.524 --> 00:16:57.722
My Uncle Ferdie has two tacky velvet
paintings. He loves those clowns.


180
00:16:57.895 --> 00:17:03.629
There are standards, technique,
composition, color, even subject.


181
00:17:03.801 --> 00:17:06.793
So if you're suggesting
that rotted side of meat is art...


182
00:17:06.971 --> 00:17:10.134
...much less good art,
then what are we going to learn?


183
00:17:11.308 --> 00:17:12.866
Just that.

184
00:17:13.043 --> 00:17:16.604
You have outlined our new syllabus,
Betty. Thank you.


185
00:17:16.780 --> 00:17:19.681
What is art?
What makes it good or bad?


186
00:17:19.850 --> 00:17:21.818
And who decides?

187
00:17:22.786 --> 00:17:24.253
Next slide, please.

188
00:17:26.290 --> 00:17:29.350
Twenty-five years ago someone
thought this was brilliant.


189
00:17:29.526 --> 00:17:31.790
- I can see that.
- Who?


190
00:17:31.962 --> 00:17:35.489
My mother. I painted it
for her birthday.


191
00:17:35.666 --> 00:17:39.864
Next slide. This is my mom.

192
00:17:40.471 --> 00:17:43.770
- Is it art?
- It's a snapshot.


193
00:17:43.941 --> 00:17:47.877
If I told you Ansel Adams had taken it,
would that make a difference?


194
00:17:48.946 --> 00:17:53.349
- Art isn't art until someone says it is.
- It's art!


195
00:17:54.618 --> 00:17:57.348
- The right people.
- Who are they?


196
00:17:57.554 --> 00:17:58.919
Betty Warren!

197
00:17:59.089 --> 00:18:02.650
- We're lucky we have one right here.
- Screw you.


198
00:18:04.461 --> 00:18:06.827
Could you go back
to the Soutine, please?


199
00:18:09.166 --> 00:18:13.193
Just look at it again.
Look beyond the paint.


200
00:18:13.370 --> 00:18:18.239
Let us try to open our minds
to a new idea.


201
00:18:21.178 --> 00:18:25.239
All right, back to chapter three.
Has anyone read it?


202
00:18:27.518 --> 00:18:28.542
Okay.

203
00:18:31.955 --> 00:18:34.890
"When your courses are set,
and a dream boat you've met...


204
00:18:35.059 --> 00:18:37.084
...have a real cigarette.
Have a Camel."


205
00:18:37.261 --> 00:18:41.288
I've got my courses, I've got my Camel
cigarette. Where is my dream boat?


206
00:18:41.465 --> 00:18:44.992
- Giselle, where is my dream boat?
- Betty's cousin isn't good enough?


207
00:18:45.169 --> 00:18:47.194
- I haven't met him.
- Don't encourage her.


208
00:18:47.371 --> 00:18:49.931
He's only escorting
Connie as a favor.


209
00:18:50.107 --> 00:18:52.041
Why are you like this?

210
00:18:52.710 --> 00:18:54.803
I didn't mean that.

211
00:18:54.978 --> 00:18:57.640
I'm just under so much pressure
with the wedding.


212
00:18:57.815 --> 00:19:00.784
Do you realize November 2
is three weeks from now?


213
00:19:00.951 --> 00:19:02.885
- Oh, honey.
- Don't have it.


214
00:19:03.053 --> 00:19:04.680
- Don't come.
- Here. Here.


215
00:19:04.855 --> 00:19:08.052
I'm working on table seating now,
so I can just erase your name.


216
00:19:08.225 --> 00:19:09.487
- Can I see it?
- No.


217
00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:11.685
Let me look.
I can't look for a second?


218
00:19:11.862 --> 00:19:15.263
- You want to see where Bill is sitting.
- No. That is over. Right?


219
00:19:15.432 --> 00:19:18.094
Right? Giselle, right?

220
00:19:20.104 --> 00:19:21.628
Damn it.

221
00:19:27.678 --> 00:19:31.136
- Do I look a little bit like her?
- Like who?


222
00:19:31.648 --> 00:19:35.106
- Katherine Watson.
- You mean, "crap is art"?


223
00:19:35.853 --> 00:19:40.119
- I think she's fabulous.
- Well, no man wanted her.


224
00:19:41.525 --> 00:19:43.686
- She isn't dead.
- She's at least 30.


225
00:19:43.861 --> 00:19:46.921
- Oh, no. No.
- I guess she never wanted children.


226
00:19:47.097 --> 00:19:49.031
For your information...

227
00:19:49.199 --> 00:19:55.229
...Katherine Watson had to take
this job to escape from California.


228
00:19:55.939 --> 00:19:57.201
Please.

229
00:19:57.374 --> 00:20:01.276
She had a torrid affair
with a Hollywood movie star.


230
00:20:01.445 --> 00:20:05.779
- She came here to get away.
- That's ridiculous.


231
00:20:05.949 --> 00:20:08.679
- Who was it?
- I don't know.


232
00:20:09.153 --> 00:20:11.747
Who was it, Giselle?
Don't be a pimple! Tell me!


233
00:20:11.922 --> 00:20:14.618
- It's ridiculous.
- Tell me. No, it's not. You know.


234
00:20:14.792 --> 00:20:18.421
- You know something. Tell me.
